B>>
B> > > American Soul
B> > >
B> > >
B> > > We'll go forward from this moment by Leonard Pitts Jr.
B> > > of the Miami Herald
B> > >
B> > > "It's my job to have something to say. They pay me to
B> > > provide words that help make sense of that which
B> > > troubles the American soul. But in this moment of
B> > > airless shock when hot tears sting disbelieving eyes,
B> > > the only thing I can find to say, the only words that
B> > > seem to fit, must be addressed to the unknown author
B> > > of this suffering.
B> > >
B> > > "You monster. You beast. You unspeakable bastard."
B> > > What lesson did you hope to teach us by your coward's
B> > > attack on our World Trade Center, our Pentagon, us?
B> > > What was it you hoped we would learn? Whatever it was,
B> > > please know that you failed.
B> > >
B> > > "Did you want us to respect your cause? You just
B> > > damned your cause.
B> > >
B> > > "Did you want to make us fear? You just steeled our
B> > > resolve.
B> > >
B> > > "Did you want to tear us apart? You just brought us
B> > > together.
B> > >
B> > > "Let me tell you about my people. We are a vast and
B> > > quarrelsome family, a family rent by racial, social,
B> > > political and class division, but a family
B> > > nonetheless. We're frivolous, yes, capable of
B> > > expending tremendous emotional energy on pop cultural
B> > > minutiae-a singer's revealing dress, a ball team's
B> > > misfortune, a cartoon mouse. We're wealthy, too,
B> > > spoiled by the ready availability of trinkets and
B> > > material goods, and maybe because of that, we walk
B> > > through life with a certain sense of blithe
B> > > entitlement. We are fundamentally decent, though-
B> > > peace-loving and compassionate. We struggle to know
B> > > the right thing and to do it. And we are, the
B> > > overwhelming majority of us, people of faith,
B> > > believers in a just and loving God.
B> > >
B> > > "Some people-you, perhaps-think that any or all
B> > > of this makes us weak. You're mistaken. We are not
B> > > weak. Indeed, we are strong in ways that cannot be
B> > > measured by arsenals.
B> > >
B> > > "Yes, we're in pain now. We are in mourning and we are
B> > > in shock. We're still grappling with the unreality of
B> > > the awful thing you did, still working to make
B> > > ourselves understand that this isn't a special effect
B> > > from some Hollywood blockbuster, isn't the plot
B> > > development from a Tom Clancy novel. Both in terms of
B> > > the awful scope of their ambition and the probable
B> > > final death toll, your attacks are likely to go down
B> > > as the worst acts of terrorism in the history of the
B> > > United States and, probably, the history of the world.
B> > > You've bloodied us as we have never been bloodied
B> > > before.
B> > >
B> > > "But there's a gulf of difference between making us
B> > > bloody and making us fall. This is the lesson Japan
B> > > was taught to its bitter sorrow the last time anyone
B> > > hit us this hard, the last time anyone brought us such
B> > > abrupt and monumental pain. When roused, we are
B> > > righteous in our outrage, terrible in our force. When
B> > > provoked by this level of barbarism, we will bear any
B> > > suffering, pay any cost, go to any length, in the
B> > > pursuit of justice.
B> > >
B> > > "I tell you this without fear of contradiction. I know
B> > > my people, as you, I think, do not. What I know
B> > > reassures me. It also causes me to tremble with dread
B> > > of the future.
B> > >
B> > > "In the days to come, there will be recrimination and
B> > > accusation, fingers pointing to determine whose
B> > > failure allowed this to happen and what can be done to
B> > > prevent it from happening again. There will be
B> > > heightened security, misguided talk of revoking basic
B> > > freedoms. We'll go forward from this moment sobered,
B> > > chastened, sad. But determined, too. Unimaginably
B> > > determined.
B> > >
B> > > "You see, the steel in us is not always readily
B> > > apparent. That aspect of our character is seldom
B> > > understood by people who don't know us well. On this
B> > > day, the family's bickering is put on hold.
B> > >
B> > > "As Americans we will weep, as Americans we will
B> > > mourn, and as Americans, we will rise in defense of
B> > > all that we cherish.
B> > >
B> > > "So I ask again: What was it you hoped to teach us?
B> > > It occurs to me that maybe you just wanted us to know
B> > > the depths of your hatred. If that's the case,
B> > > consider the message received.
B> > >
B> > > And take this message in exchange:
B> > > You don't know my people. You don't know what we're
B> > > capable of. You don't know what you just started.
B> > >
B> > > "But you're about to learn."
B> >
B> >
B> >
B> >
B> >
